description.text:
A FAIRTRADE cookie cutter and stamp.

This is how you make the cookies:

Make a light colored dough suitable to be cut with the cutter. Put on baking paper and roll thin. Stamp the logos in a grid like pattern and remove the access dough, leaving just the logos.
Bake that.
When it's done, let it cool. Leave the logos on the paper for now.
Melt chocolate, and pour it over the logos, covering them maybe 1/8" (3mm) deep.
Let this cool until the chocolate has cured, but is still slightly soft.
Put new baking paper over it, then a cutting board or some such, and turn everything over (courage needed).
Remove the original baking paper - you should see the baked dough logos embedded in the chocolate.
Use a pizza roller to cut the chocolate between the Cookies, but leave room for the letters. Then use either stamp to press the letters into the chocolate under each logo.
Let all this cool overnight.

Use the cookies to educate people about fairtrade!

Do send me a picture of your cookies, please!!! ;-)

These models of the Vietnam War Memorial Wall in Washington DC were created for Memorial Day 2016. http://www.thewall-usa.com/index.asp

The Memorial Wall was designed by Maya Lin in 1982. The design was controversial at the time but if you visit the memorial you will see that it is a deeply moving and appropriate way to remember the thousands of soldiers that died in the conflict.

There are replicas of the wall in WIldwood NJ, Pensacola FL, and WInfield KS, and several traveling replicas.

title: 3D FPV Camera and TX for Skyzone and similar

description.text:
This is a replacement 3d camera for the Skyzone 3d goggle set. This unit is 2/3 lighter, has wider spaced cameras for an enhanced 3d effect at greater distances and has the cameras and transmitters contained in the same unit. It is about gopro sized and easily fits a 250 quad. I have included a photo showing its size compared to the stock unit and its separate transmitter. I use it for fixed wing flying with my bixler. It has good range with 2x 600mW transmitters. It can also be used with any 3d set up that uses separate channels for each eye.

Parts needed:
2 x TS5828 micro 600mW transmitters (widely available on ebay)
2 x 700tvl miniature cameras with 15mm x15mm body (also widely available on ebay)
1 small amount of Vero board
2 suitable heat sinks (optional)
Connectors will come with the cameras and transmitters, but you might need 2 servo connectors for powere and OSD connection.

Set the 2 transmitters to radiate on 5771Mhz for the right eye and 5733 for the left. This is the default setting for the Skyzone goggles in 3D mode. If you need to change this you can (RTFM)

Look at my diagram and wire up the cameras and transmitters as shown. Use a small bit of veroboard that will fit in the compartment provided. If you don't want to use veroboard just connect it all together and save a bit of room!

If you are using the same voltage for the Camera and TX you can join the Vcc track and just use one power feed from the OSD. Otherwise use separate power feeds. The Vector for example provides 2 regulated feeds for the camera and tx. They can both be 12 volts or one 5v and the other 12v.

If you do not want to use OSD, Just connect the OSD out data lead to the OSD in data lead (bridge the tracks on the Veroboard.

You may have noticed that the OSD is only on one channel. Don't worry this is good. You wont notice and as the osd is in the foreground, you get added depth perception.

When you have wired the loom, insert the cameras, make sure they are a tight fit and congruent. (They must be exactly parallel) You might not want to glue them yet as there is a bit of wiggle room if you need to make adjustments. Insert the Transmitters, heat sinks facing inwards. The Transmitters come without heat sinks but they get a tad too hot for my liking so I added Heat sinks. Make sure the fins in the heat sinks are fore and aft to go with the airflow.

Attach the antennas and tighten onto the Transmitters to fix the transmitters in place. Attach the loom connections to TXs and Cameras and you are good to test.

If you don't get the 3d effect it is likely you have got the wrong camera going to the wrong channel, just swap the TX connectors over.

Make sure that registration of the 3d image is good (no double image or ghosting) If it is not wiggle the cameras until good. When good glue them in position. A blob of hot glue on each would be fine.

description.text: A snap together cousin of the super stratos (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:97803) , this glueless design offers similar performance without the mess....ideal for young makers to build, without worrying about stuck fingers! Files are provided to licencee to make unlimited models from these files for licensees personal use. Commercial use of any kind, or other uses not specifically allowed are explicitly disallowed. Description: An efficient conventional glider with glueless assembly, ideal for looping flights and long glides. Plastic: ABS Layers: .20mm Fill: 25% Perimeters: 2 Solid Layers: 2 filament use / weight (3mm) : Approx 1350mm Orientation:
first layer lentghwise (0 degrees to fuselage), altrenate by 90 degrees. A 45 degree (or non right angle) axis will cause asymetrical wing warping under load (bad). Build Notes:
Allow to cool before carefully removing from build platform. The wings are easily deformed during removal, and must be absoultely symmetrical for proper flight. Removal with a very thin plastic spatula (print one!) is preferred. Test fit all parts and trim if necesary prior to final assembly. The dihedral joint is assembled by clamping along the top of the fuselage between the wings with the dihederal clip to establish dihedral angle. Clip is most asiliy installed one corner at a time mid chord and then slid fully foreward into place. Remove any adhesions, test clip and adust as necescary prior to assembly to achieve a symmetrical dihedral angle. Insert (snap) the hook into the canopy one end at a time, pointed canopy end and open jaw of hook facing the same direction. Snap the hook / canopy assemby into the fuselage. Slide tail into place being sure to insert the pitch adjustment tab into the elevator slot. Flight Notes: Launching is by hand or with a 1/16" to 1/8" rubber band. Test and adjust by hand launching first. A slight elevator - up reflex is required for non-inverted flight. This is accomplished by adjusting the rudder locking tab to less or more engaged in the fuselage. there are two settings and a latch to prevent unwanted movement. A gradual test/adjust cycle is recommended. To correct turning or spiraling, differential elevator control (elevon) is preferred, though some aileron bending may be needed if the wings are warped from improper bed removal. Carefully bend this in with finger pressure, but avoid creasing or excessive strain.

description.text: This is an enclosure for David Crocker's mini IR height sensor board. It protects the board from filament. In case the sensor is used with an untreated or clear anodized aluminium board, a an optical filter can be installed in front of the sensor and the LEDs. I used a cheap film polarizer that can be bought off ebay and cut to size. My polarizer works in the NIR and transmits ~25% of light. The light passes twice through the polarizer (once on the way from the LED to the print bed and once after the reflection from the print bed on the way to the sensor). Although the reflection on aluminium will change the polarisation slightly, this proves to be an advantage when the printer is used where the ambient NIR can influence the sensor. When the polariser is cut at the right angle it can eliminate unwanted influences from sunlight. A film polariser can be bought off ebay relatively cheap. Depending on the material, two films may be stacked at an angle to attenuate the light as desired.

The dihedral joint is assembled by clamping along the top of the fuselage between the wings with the dihederal clip to establish dihedral angle. Insert (snap) the hook into the canopy one end at a time, pointed canopy end and open jaw of hook facing the same direction. Snap the hook / canopy assemby into the fuselage. Slide tails into place being sure to fully insert the locking tabs. Flight Notes: Launching is by hand or with a 1/16" to 1/8" rubber band. Test and adjust by launching with a small rubber band partially extended. After proper trim is achieved, stronger bands may be used. A slight elevon - up reflex is provided by the twin tails. The skeleton canopy can be used to provide a lighter lose for slower or more aerobatic flights. A gradual test/adjust cycle is recommended. title: Grave Marker for Civil War Veteran (Grand Army of the Republic)

description.text:
At the oldest cemetery in Sioux Falls, SD are a number of Civil War veterans. Many of them have a military grave marker with an adjoining metal flag holder indicating they were members of the G.A.R. or the Grand Army of the Republic.

This particular stone belongs to H. W. Lewis of Company C of the 22nd Infantry of the Wisconsin Infantry.

I created this model from 38 photos using a Sony A5100 in RAW mode with a Nikon Series E 35mm 1:2.5 lens on an adapter.

I chose this stone at random and used a tripod to take a series of overlapping photos using my Sony A5100 in RAW mode with a Nikon Series E 35mm 1:2.5 lens via an adapter.

I took a total of 38 photos around the stone and a few closer shots of the front of the G.A.R. star. Somehow, I overlooked getting adequate coverage for the very top of the grave stone!

At home, I converted all the Sony ARW raw files to DNG files, imported them into Photomatix Pro, and settled on a conservative HDR output in TIF.

After double-checking all the files to be sure of even tones and exposures, I opened the folder in Photoscan and used the 'Medium' setting from start to finish. It took roughly an hour to transform the 38 photos into a good model of H. W. Lewis' grave stone.

The only thing left to do was open the model in Meshmixer to repair the hole at the top of the grave stone and do some slight editing before exporting it as a OBJ & PLY file to share here.

description.text: I like the living hinge idea very much, but think it's just as useful in a static context where the wood stays in one place. I like the idea of being able to make curved wooden objects by pinning the hinge in a particular position.

Cut the pattern for both the 'sling' and the stand on a laser cutter; this design is for 1/8" plywood. Snap the pieces together by putting the tabs into the holes. It should require no glue. You may want to curve the hinge around a bottle or similar circular object.
As with all laser cut objects, be mindful of the laser kerf and focus. For the hinge, you'll probably get the best result if the scoring is parallel with the grain of the wood, although since the hinge won't move, you can get away with against the grain if you must.
If you have thicker plywood, you'll need to change the size of the tabs and receiving holes to match.

comments.text: Major differences with the OSC Flex 1 are the additional custom aluminum parts, larger build volume (220x220x220) and the lead screw upgrade on the Z axis which creates almost perfect walls on your prints.  The aluminum part files were created using software provided by eMachineShop.  That is also the company where I order them from.  You will need to go to their website to download their software to be able to open the part files and see dimensions there.  Sorry about that.  Also, the lead screw upgrade doesn't have a complete 3D printed part version, so make sure you completely decide what you are doing first.  You could use original flexMendel 3D printed parts as a starting point, but what kept happening was any time plastic parts are exposed to continuous stress or force (like the parts we replaced with aluminum parts) the plastic starts to "creep" and you will have to continuously be checking and tightening your X and Y belts.  With the aluminum parts, you are able to use continuous belts and essentially will only require belt re-calibrations maybe once a year depending on use.

For the Basic Organiser, print these 4 thing files (Lid, Box, Slides, and Locks). You should have 10 slides and 2 Locks. This will store 10 pairs of earrings.

This is a battery holder for 3 double A batteries. It is a test to get all the dimensions right so that I can use the design in my robotics projects.

The design is based around Keystone Electronics parts (5221, 5212, 5222) available on mouser.com (among others).

Print the thing. Solder wires to the 5221 and 5222. Snap the parts into position as shown in the picture (two 5212s in the larger slots, the 5221/5222 in smaller slots). Make sure there is a spring opposite each button.

In this version, the wire holes are a little small. Use the holes as a pilot to drill to a size that fits your desired wire size.

I got data sheets for the AA batteries and battery terminals. I designed the solid modles in solidworks. I made a bunch of experimental prints and dinked with the parameters until everything fit. Saved it as an STL and printed using my flashforge creator pro with black abs thread.

description.text: The key and wallet wall hook was designed to help organize my things when I would come home from school. Its a simple design that allows me to organize my keys, wallets and even hang my watches, and sunglasses.

Printer:

QIDI

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

200 microns

Infill:

25%
Rendered in SolidWorks

SolidWorks

I designed this utilizing SolidWorks. This is actually my second version of the key and wallet hook which allows me to hold both my regular wallet and my skinny wallet. It is actually an assembly of two separate part files, the shell and the hook.

The shell consists of a rectangle being extruded into a cube, I then cut out the inside to make it a shell. I created two separate pockets in order to be able to store my small wallet and my regular wallet separately by creating a small wall there. I then cut out small rectangles in the floor, this gives the same structural integrity but still allowing the manufacturing to use less material. I placed to small holes on the back wall of the shell, and this allows for the key & wallet hook to be either thumbtacked to the wall via the two holes or just taped to the wall utilizing 3M removable wall tape.

Rendered image of the shell

From the shell I created the hook as a separate part file in SolidWorks. I first created an extruded circle and then on a perpendicular surface created a half circle and swept the diameter of the extruded circle around the half circle, thus creating a hook.

Rendered image of a hook

At this point I created an assembly file where I imported the hooks into my extruded shell. I then placed three hooks onto the front of the shell and then two offsetting hooks on each side of the shell.

This design with two separate components, the hook and the shell, allows for unique and customizable placements of the hook and each size of your wallet.

description.header: Project: Creating your own personal key & wallet hook
description.text:
Overall & Background

You will learn the significant of structural integrity and the cost associated in saving material. You will also become familiar with reverse engineering in projects. It will also teach a new student the basics of 3D printing and CAD models. This project will also familiarize the student to assemblies of models.

Objective:

-Be able to 3D print a unique and customized key and wallet hook
-Stretch the limits of 3D printing with supports
-Learn the basic steps of 3D CAD (SolidWorks)
-Create a customizable project to your needs and desires

Audiences:

-Anyone who is new to 3D printing or that wants to create useful products for themselves

Subject:

-Basic engineering
-Math
-CAD and 3D modeling

Skills Learned:

-3D Printing
-Assembly Modeling
-Reverse Engineering
-3D CAD
-Structural Integrity
-Engineering Report (How to write an engineering report)

Lesson/Activity:

Step 1:

Gather your wallets, keys and watches that you would like to organize. At this point the student must measure the height, width and depth of the wallet this will determine the size of the shell to create.

Step 2:

Download or open any 3D modeling program, many are free to download on the internet (SolidWorks, Autodesk, tinkercad). I chose to create my project in SolidWorks, as I'm most comfortable with this program. Please refer to the "How I Designed This" section for more details. Start by creating two separet assemblies one being the shell that holds the wallet, and another being the hook that holds the wallet and keys.

Step 3:

Now create an assembly placing the hook onto the shell. Use the mate feature to attach the hook in feasible locations to place your keys and watches.

Step 4:

Upon completion of printing and designing each project the student should then begin to write up a report. The report should include, the problem and their design solution to solve the problem, instructions on how to recreate the project, any references used, any unique design solutions. The teacher may also require the students to put together an estimated project budget and schedule in order to better prepare the students for engineering.

Duration:

The duration for a teacher to complete this project with there students can take any where from a few hours to a few days depending on the experience the students have. It also may depends on the printing time of this project, and the printer.

Preperation:

Students should have minimal experience with 3D modeling, and reverse engineering or measuring objects. They should also be able to work a 3D printer and calipers.

Materials Required:
-Wallet, Keys, Watches
-Calipers or ruler
-Computer with 3D modeling program installed
-3D printer

References:

Here are some basic instructions on 3D modeling.
http://www.instructables.com/id/Intro-to-3D-Modeling/

Rubric and Assesment:

Reverse engineering
• How accurate are the measurements of the length, width, and height?
• Does the wallet fit inside the shell?

Hook Placement
• Do the keys and watched fit on the hooks?
• Is the placement of the hooks agronomical?

3D Modeling
• How efficient were the steps taken to create the object?
• Did the student think about areas that don’t require all the plastic?

Print Quality
• Did the student utilize proper supports, and fill percentage?
• Did the student understand the tradeoff of print time and print quality?

Handouts and Assets:

The rubric in the previous section above can be used to help assist the students design there project, as well as the teacher to grade the project.

title: TRS-80/Tandy Color Computer Raspberry Pi (B+, 2B, 3B) Case

description.text:
This is a Raspberry Pi case shaped like the original Tandy CoCo. The astute reader will notice that the keyboard has been upgraded. ;) The model is slightly cartoonish, but it came out decent and the ports are all pretty much where you'd expect them if you've seen a Color Computer. Card slot on the right side, video/audio/power in the back. There are some extra cutouts on the left for the USB and network ports as well. I made this based on a suggestion in the Color Computer Facebook group that it was too easy to find cases shaped like other classic systems and not easy enough to find one shaped like a CoCo. Problem solved.

This fits my Raspberry Pi B+. Google tells me it should also fit the 2B and 3B. There should be enough room in the case for a small heatsink if you need it.

Printer:

Monoprice Maker Architect

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Infill:

Probably doesn't matter. I used 10%.

Notes:

The .stl files used to be 1.065x larger than the OpenSCAD source. This was the scaling I had to use on the last project I made to get the final product to come out the right size. I've saled them back down because I've found that the Makerbot (which is pretty much a de-facto standard) prints them at roughly the original size. Be careful. You may still need to resize it to fit. The Raspberry Pi board should fit horizontally in the box, exactly. You will not need to flex the board. It will then have just enough room to slide right into the back of the case. You'll need to tilt it, and you may need to wiggle it vertically a bit in order to get the board to lock into place between the stand-off and the pin pieces in the back of the case. The headphone jack fits exactly into its port on mine, and the rest are very close too.

Supports are built in where needed, and rafts are probably more trouble than they're worth here. There are a number of different pieces available here in case you want to print the keys or the keyboard frame in a different color. If not, the print is very easy. You can just print the box and the lid piece with the built-in keyboard. This comes out very clean.

You'll need to probably use some needle-nose pliers and a file or a knife to remove the built-in supports. Pull them out from between the vents, and out of the side ports on the box. If you've printed the keyboard holder without the keyboard in it, there will be a few small ones in the front/top of that piece. Also on my printer, I need to clip a small disk that forms when the lid is started. If the disk isn't clipped off, the lid doesn't fit properly.

This was an interesting model. It's complicated enough that I thought the easy way would be to model the entire system at once. Once that was done I built a stand-in model for the Raspberry Pi and used the OpenSCAD difference() function to hollow-out a Pi-shaped chamber, complete with ports in the correct spots and so on. I added some padding around the board except for where the case stand-offs were supposed to land. This left me with a hollow CoCo-shaped model into which a Pi should fit.

After that, there's the matter of getting the board into the case. I decided that it would be best to be able to slide it in from the front. The keyboard facade seemed like a good place. I made a small cube which, when used with difference() would punch out a door in the front of the case. I thought that I'd just use intersection() to get the keyboard piece that was punched out. This worked fine, but when printed it was too tight a fit. I ended up taking the intersection() with a cube that was slightly smaller in two dimensions in order to make it work. The final thing was just to add some spherical tabs to hold the keyboard piece in.

The finished product is such that the Pi slides in and out of the case. Once it's snapped together, it's held in place by the lid, the back ports, and the fittings inside of the case.

This is a small puzzle box that is intended to contain a nickel. I have uploaded three different models. Each model requires the use of a different sized small ball. The intent is that you can choose the model size to match whatever size small plastic ball / round bead you happen to have on hand. Part of the trick involves the plastic bead to see the full solution and how the box works you can take a look at the video included in the photos or click on this link. https://youtu.be/UGnz6Ecnk24

The model is sized to use a 10-24 screw and nut to hold the puzzle together. I start with a 1.25 inch long screw and cut it to length after I see how thick the puzzle is. The puzzle thickness varies with the ball diameter.

I also include the model files for a 3D printed mold that you can use to make your own small balls from hot glue. There is more information on the mold and molding process in the video. The mold prints should be printed with a finer resolution (I used .1mm layers).

comments.text:
Nice idea but... 3d prints are not food safe by nature. Between print lines / layers it's full of micro holes that accumulate millions of bacteria that are impossible to remove. I was reading that the only way a 3d print could be food safe is by adding a superficial treatment like with an epoxy resin specific to be food safe.
I'm sorry as I had some food related designs too... :(

Made a small version of a groundstation I can carry around on my backpack. I use it on a cheap GorillaPod clone, but any tripod with 1/4" screw will work

Holds my FR632, and a lipo battery. Cables and everything can be mounted with Velcro straps, the small hook on the backside can hold my goggles. The lipo Tray is a bit lager than my 2200mAh SLS battery so I could use some padding on the sides.

  • direct printed 1/4" thread
  • pilot hole for 1/4" thread
